37887>>>    // Add code to customize your Zoom View based on how it was invoked.
37887>>>    // Use NavigateData to determine the context this view will be used in.
37887>>>    Procedure OnNavigateForward tWebNavigateData NavigateData Integer hoInvokingView Integer hoInvokingObject
37890>>>
37890>>>        // if this view is being used in multiple contexts, you may need a block of code
37890>>>        // like this to handle customizations. This would include hiding rows and buttons
37890>>>        // (WebSet pbRender) and changing the values of various captions.
37890>>>        Case Begin
37890>>>            Case (NavigateData.eNavigateType = nfFromMain)
37892>>>                // If from main, this is a probably a main file Select to Zoom.
37892>>>                // This is the most typical way to navigate to a zoom.
37892>>>                Case Break
37893>>>                
37893>>>            Case (NavigateData.eNavigateType = nfFromParent)
37896>>>                // If from parent, this is a constrained drill down.
37896>>>                // If needed, you could check NavigateData.iTable to determine the constraining parent.
37896>>>                // This would be unusual - normally you drill down from a parent to a list (Select view).
37896>>>                Case Break
37897>>>                
37897>>>            Case (NavigateData.eNavigateType = nfFromChild)
37900>>>                // If from child, this is a probably a parent Zoom from a Zoom. 
37900>>>                // This is unusual, but it might be used for adding a new child record.
37900>>>                Case Break
37901>>>                
37901>>>            Case Else // must be nfUndefined
37901>>>                // This may be the start of a query or this may be used for some kind of custom operation.
37901>>>                // You may want to check NavigateData.NamedValues.
37901>>>                  
37901>>>        Case End
37901>>>
37901>>>        // Action buttons can be changed dynamically during a Zoom's display lifetime.
37901>>>        // It's best to set these buttons in their own procedure so you can change later.
37901>>>        Send SetActionButtons
37902>>>
37902>>>    End_Procedure
37903>>>
37903>>>End_Object
